00:47:33,948 --> 00:47:37,349
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Yeah, I vote for that.
-Are you kidding? We have to get higher!

533
00:47:37,751 --> 00:47:39,184
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Come on.

534
00:47:39,353 --> 00:47:41,548
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Up to the library.

535
00:47:41,722 --> 00:47:44,350
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Calm down.

536
00:47:44,525 --> 00:47:46,459
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I can't understand what you're saying.

537
00:47:48,929 --> 00:47:51,090
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}If you stay calm, ma'am,
I'll get you out.

538
00:47:56,705 --> 00:47:59,037
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}The door is jammed!

539
00:48:00,075 --> 00:48:01,406
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I don't speak French!

540
00:48:36,978 --> 00:48:38,275
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Hey, where's Laura?

541
00:48:40,348 --> 00:48:44,478
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-She was just right there.
-She's right there! Right there, see?

542
00:48:44,653 --> 00:48:46,120
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}What is she doing?

543
00:48:46,288 --> 00:48:49,018
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Tell them to cover their eyes.

544
00:49:12,314 --> 00:49:16,842
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}There is a wall of water coming towards
New York City. Everybody--

545
00:50:01,564 --> 00:50:03,862
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-What?
-Her bag's in the cab. Their passports.

546
00:50:04,033 --> 00:50:06,092
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Forget about it.

547
00:50:06,268 --> 00:50:08,429
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-I'll get it for her.
-Come on.

548
00:50:15,011 --> 00:50:16,273
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Oh, my....

549
00:50:22,418 --> 00:50:24,511
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Laura!

550
00:50:29,291 --> 00:50:30,918
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Laura!

551
00:50:31,927 --> 00:50:33,861
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Sam.
-No! Brian, no!

552
00:50:34,030 --> 00:50:36,225
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Laura! Laura, look!

553
00:50:36,399 --> 00:50:38,060
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Come on. Come!

554
00:50:38,868 --> 00:50:40,460
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Come on!

555
00:50:42,939 --> 00:50:44,338
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam!

556
00:51:24,147 --> 00:51:25,704
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Professor.

557
00:51:26,715 --> 00:51:28,113
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Thank you.

558
00:51:29,518 --> 00:51:32,850
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-ls that Neville's handiwork?
-Neville's way beyond stick figures.

559
00:51:33,021 --> 00:51:34,817
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-He's 6 already.
-Oh.

560
00:51:34,990 --> 00:51:37,958
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}No, this masterpiece belongs
to my second grandson, David.

561
00:51:38,126 --> 00:51:41,288
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}God. I can't believe Neville's 6 already.

562
00:51:45,133 --> 00:51:47,066
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}You won't believe how fast they grow.

563
00:51:49,404 --> 00:51:51,234
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I've got Jack Hall on the phone.

564
00:51:51,640 --> 00:51:53,800
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}They've run the data we've sent them.

565
00:51:55,343 --> 00:51:56,900
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Here he is.

566
00:51:59,748 --> 00:52:03,205
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Jack, were you able to recreate
the thermal cycle?

567
00:52:03,385 --> 00:52:05,249
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Yes. The storm's rotation...

568
00:52:05,420 --> 00:52:09,583
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}...is pulling super-cooled air all the way
down from the upper troposphere.

569
00:52:11,593 --> 00:52:15,585
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}But shouldn't the air warm up
before it reaches ground level?

570
00:52:15,764 --> 00:52:20,063
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It should. But it doesn 't.
The air's descending too rapidly.

571
00:52:21,069 --> 00:52:23,593
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Is this an isolated incident?

572
00:52:26,141 --> 00:52:28,040
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I'm afraid not.

573
00:52:28,210 --> 00:52:31,576
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}We've located two supercells
in addition to the one over Scotland.

574
00:52:31,746 --> 00:52:33,372
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}One over Northern Canada...

575
00:52:33,548 --> 00:52:36,539
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}...and another one over Siberia.

576
00:52:36,718 --> 00:52:39,345
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}And do we know their projected paths?

577
00:52:39,521 --> 00:52:40,817
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Yes.

578
00:52:40,989 --> 00:52:44,253
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Our previous estimates of six to
eight weeks weren 't even close.

579
00:52:44,426 --> 00:52:47,952
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}This one storm is going to change
the face of our planet.

580
00:52:48,130 --> 00:52:51,997
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Here's a projection of 24 hours out.

581
00:52:56,738 --> 00:52:59,001
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}This is 48 hours out.

582
00:53:00,742 --> 00:53:03,642
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}And in seven to 1 0 days....

583
00:53:06,748 --> 00:53:09,011
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}When this storm is over...

584
00:53:09,184 --> 00:53:11,981
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}... we 'll be in a new ice age.

585
00:53:16,024 --> 00:53:17,888
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}My God.

586
00:53:36,143 --> 00:53:38,042
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Professor...

587
00:53:38,212 --> 00:53:40,202
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}...it' s time you got out of there.

588
00:53:42,216 --> 00:53:45,378
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I'm afraid that time has
come and gone, my friend.

589
00:53:50,424 --> 00:53:52,721
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}What can we do?

590
00:53:55,930 --> 00:53:58,454
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Save as many as you can.

591
00:54:13,380 --> 00:54:15,074
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Jack...

592
00:54:15,249 --> 00:54:17,478
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}...something's happened in New York.

593
00:54:28,062 --> 00:54:30,894
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}No, the power is out.
I've been in here all day.

594
00:54:31,065 --> 00:54:34,158
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Who needs help?
-Here. Over here.

595
00:54:40,908 --> 00:54:42,568
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}What?

596
00:54:43,444 --> 00:54:46,708
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}This is the last one. Enjoy it.

597
00:54:46,880 --> 00:54:48,403
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Greedy.

598
00:54:49,617 --> 00:54:51,982
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}All circuits are busy at this time.

599
00:54:52,152 --> 00:54:54,142
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Listen, thanks for coming back for me.

600
00:54:55,956 --> 00:54:57,650
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It was really brave.

601
00:55:09,736 --> 00:55:12,135
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I guess I better return her bag.

602
00:55:29,422 --> 00:55:30,786
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam?

603
00:55:31,291 --> 00:55:33,349
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Just tell her how you feel.

604
00:55:37,397 --> 00:55:38,886
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Yeah.

605
00:55:44,003 --> 00:55:47,665
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Did you reach your little brother yet?
-No, there's still no service.

606
00:55:47,840 --> 00:55:49,864
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Damn cell phones.

607
00:55:54,080 --> 00:55:57,378
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Excuse me. Are there any
pay phones on the upper floors?

608
00:55:57,550 --> 00:55:59,141
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}No, no, no.

609
00:55:59,319 --> 00:56:01,343
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-There are some on the mezzanine.
-Great.

610
00:56:01,521 --> 00:56:04,546
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-But I think it's underwater.
-Where you going? Power's out.

611
00:56:04,724 --> 00:56:07,214
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Older payphones draw power
directly from the line.

612
00:56:07,393 --> 00:56:10,919
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}There will be an emergency meeting
of all NOAA department heads....

613
00:56:11,698 --> 00:56:14,564
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Oh, God. I've been trying to reach Sam.

614
00:56:14,734 --> 00:56:16,462
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}So have l.

615
00:56:17,136 --> 00:56:19,069
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I tried to call
and couldn't get you.

616
00:56:19,238 --> 00:56:21,262
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It's been a madhouse here. Come on.

617
00:56:26,913 --> 00:56:29,142
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Are you sure about this?

618
00:56:39,225 --> 00:56:40,521
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It works.

619
00:56:45,932 --> 00:56:47,421
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I love that picture.

620
00:56:47,600 --> 00:56:49,794
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Yeah, so do l.

621
00:56:50,770 --> 00:56:52,134
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Where was that taken?

622
00:56:52,305 --> 00:56:53,601
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Miami.

623
00:56:54,073 --> 00:56:56,438
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Well, where was l?
I don't remember that trip.

624
00:56:56,609 --> 00:56:59,406
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam and I went with my sister.
You were in Alaska...

625
00:56:59,579 --> 00:57:02,479
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}...doing research on your doctorate.

626
00:57:06,284 --> 00:57:09,252
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Remember what he was like
when he was that age?

627
00:57:09,755 --> 00:57:11,949
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Everything was "one more."

628
00:57:12,124 --> 00:57:17,060
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}One more bedtime story. One more ride
on my shoulders. "One more, Daddy."

629
00:57:18,897 --> 00:57:23,128
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Jack. Sam's on the phone. Line four.

630
00:57:23,301 --> 00:57:25,165
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Sam?
-Dad!

631
00:57:25,337 --> 00:57:29,432
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Where are you? Are you all right?
-I'm all right. We're at the Public Library.

632
00:57:29,608 --> 00:57:32,508
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Sam, it's Mom. I'm so happy you're okay.
-Mom.

633
00:57:33,345 --> 00:57:36,802
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Can you call Laura and Brian's parents
and tell them we're all right?

634
00:57:36,982 --> 00:57:38,471
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Yes, of course.

635
00:57:39,684 --> 00:57:41,913
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Sam, what's that noise?
-Sam?

636
00:57:42,354 --> 00:57:44,116
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam?

637
00:57:46,324 --> 00:57:48,917
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}What is going on out there, Dad?

638
00:57:49,094 --> 00:57:51,220
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam. Sam, listen to me.

639
00:57:51,396 --> 00:57:52,828
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Listen very carefully.

640
00:57:52,998 --> 00:57:55,090
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Forget what I said about heading south.

641
00:57:55,267 --> 00:57:57,461
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It's too late.
The storm is gonna get worse.

642
00:57:58,236 --> 00:58:03,263
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}It's gonna turn into a massive blizzard with
an eye in the center, like a huge hurricane.

643
00:58:03,763 --> 00:58:06,856
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Only the air will be so cold,
you could freeze to death in seconds.

644
00:58:10,703 --> 00:58:11,964
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam?

645
00:58:12,138 --> 00:58:14,731
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Well, what should we do?
-Listen to me, son.

646
00:58:15,241 --> 00:58:16,901
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Do not go outside.

647
00:58:17,076 --> 00:58:20,010
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Burn what you can to stay warm,
and try to wait it out.

648
00:58:20,179 --> 00:58:24,171
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I will come for you. Do you understand me?
I will come for you.

649
00:58:27,320 --> 00:58:28,547
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam?

650
00:58:29,222 --> 00:58:31,746
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Sam, come back!
-Sam?

651
00:58:32,391 --> 00:58:34,358
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam, did you hear me?

652
00:58:34,527 --> 00:58:35,788
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Did you hear me?

653
00:58:38,397 --> 00:58:39,863
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Sam?

654
00:58:41,033 --> 00:58:44,991
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Tell me he's gonna be okay--
-He's gonna be all right.

655
00:58:45,171 --> 00:58:47,195
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}He's gonna be all right,
you understand?

656
00:59:14,165 --> 00:59:16,928
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I thought you'd drowned.

657
00:59:22,073 --> 00:59:25,508
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Let's find some dry clothes for you.
Come on.

658
00:59:31,483 --> 00:59:33,245
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Where'd you store the arctic gear?

659
00:59:34,386 --> 00:59:36,216
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}You can't make it to New York, Jack.

660
00:59:36,388 --> 00:59:38,719
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I've walked that far before in the snow.

661
00:59:39,591 --> 00:59:41,319
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}This is not the same.

662
00:59:41,493 --> 00:59:45,724
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Jack, this is not the same.
Lucy, tell him.

663
00:59:48,099 --> 00:59:50,259
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I have to do this.

664
00:59:52,437 --> 00:59:54,427
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I know.

665
01:00:01,179 --> 01:00:03,203
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}My hands are shak--

666
01:00:03,381 --> 01:00:06,816
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}-Shaking.
-That's okay. Here.

667
01:00:06,985 --> 01:00:08,952
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}Here. Come here.

668
01:00:12,691 --> 01:00:14,521
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}What are you doing?

669
01:00:14,693 --> 01:00:17,160
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}I'm using my body heat to warm you.

670
01:00:17,429 --> 01:00:22,559
{\fncambria\fs22\shad2\1c&H45DFEC&\b0\i1}If we let the blood from your arms and legs
